Associations between clinical variables and age-adjusted burden of driver mutations in endometrial glands

Markdown file to present the methods to examine associations between clinical variables and age-adjusted burden of driver mutations in endometrial glands. Before you start the following analyses, please convert the corresponding excel source data files to tab-delimited text files. The source data files are provided in our paper (Yamaguchi et al.Nat Commun in press).

Clean up workspace

rm(list=ls())

Load libraries

library(ggplot2)

Visualize linear relationship between age of menarche and age-adjusted burden of driver mutations

p_men <- ggplot(mutBurd, aes(x=menarche, y=driver_mutation_burden_age_adjusted))
p_men <- p_men + geom_smooth(method="lm", level=0.95, color="black", size=0.5)
p_men <- p_men + geom_point(fill="#fb8072", shape=21, colour="black", size=5, alpha=0.9)
p_men <- p_men + ylim(min(mutBurd$driver_mutation_burden_age_adjusted), max(mutBurd$driver_mutation_burden_age_adjusted))
p_men <- p_men + xlab("Age of menarche")
p_men <- p_men + ylab("Number of driver mutations\nper gland")
p_men <- p_men + theme(
  legend.position="none", 
  axis.line=element_line(colour="#d3d3d3"),
  panel.grid.major=element_line(colour="#d3d3d3"),
  panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
  panel.border=element_blank(), 
  panel.background=element_blank(),
  axis.ticks=element_blank(), 
  axis.text.x=element_text(size=20, colour="black"), 
  axis.text.y=element_text(size=20, colour="black"), 
  axis.title=element_text(size=20))

plot(p_men)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Pearson correlation coefficients between clinical variables and age-adjusted burden of driver mutations

name <- c("Menarche", "Parity", "BMI", "Pack years")
clin_var <-c("menarche", "parity", "BMI", "pack_years")
r_coef <- vector(mode="numeric", length(clin_var))
p_value <- vector(mode="numeric", length(clin_var))

for (i in 1:length(clin_var)) {
  clin_data <- mutBurd[, clin_var[i]]
  res <- cor.test(clin_data, mutBurd$driver_mutation_burden_age_adjusted)
  r_coef[i] <- res$estimate
  p_value[i] <- res$p.value
}

result_cor <- data.frame(
  clinical_variable=name,
  r=r_coef,
  p_value=p_value)

result_cor
